  'Yes, ITIN holders can get personal loans. Credit unions, community banks, and online lenders offer both secured and unsecured personal loans using an ITIN instead of an SSN. Approval and rates depend on your income and credit history. Secured loans are easier to get with thin credit, and on-time payments build your U.S. credit.';
---
<MoneyPageLayout
  title="ITIN Personal Loans: Borrow Without an SSN (2026)"
  h1="ITIN Personal Loans"
  description="How to get a personal loan with an ITIN. Secured vs unsecured options, how much you can borrow, rates, and where to find ITIN-friendly lenders."
  path="/itin-personal-loans"
  eyebrow="Personal financing"
  lede="From consolidating debt to covering an emergency, ITIN personal loans give you flexible financing without a Social Security Number. Here's how to qualify."
  quickAnswer={quickAnswer}
  faqs={faqs}
  heroImage="/img/personal-kitchen.webp"
  heroAlt="A couple cooking together in a bright kitchen"
>
  <h2>Can you get a personal loan with an ITIN?</h2>
  <p>Yes. A <strong>personal loan</strong> is a lump sum you repay in fixed monthly installments, and plenty of lenders approve them for ITIN holders. Credit unions are often the most welcoming, especially if you become a member first. Online and community lenders fill in the rest of the market.</p>

  <h2>Secured vs. unsecured options</h2>
  <p>If your credit history is thin, a <strong>secured</strong> personal loan, backed by a savings deposit, CD, or vehicle, is far easier to get and usually cheaper. As you build history, you can move to <strong>unsecured</strong> loans that need no collateral.</p>
  <table>
    <thead><tr><th>Factor</th><th>Secured</th><th>Unsecured</th></tr></thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td>Collateral</td><td>Required</td><td>None</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Easier with thin credit</td><td>Yes</td><td>No</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Typical rate</td><td>Lower</td><td>Higher</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <h2>How much can you borrow?</h2>
  <p>Loan amounts range from a few hundred dollars to <strong>$50,000 or more</strong>, depending on income, credit, and the lender. If you're newer to U.S. credit, expect to start smaller and grow your borrowing power as you demonstrate on-time payments. If you need a smaller amount fast for an emergency, see our dedicated guide to <a href="/itin-cash-loans">ITIN cash loans</a>.</p>

  <h2>Which type of lender should you start with?</h2>
  <p>Where you apply matters as much as your numbers. The ITIN holder's path usually runs through institutions that underwrite on income and documentation rather than leaning entirely on a credit score pulled by SSN. Credit unions are a common starting point: they are not-for-profit, member-owned cooperatives, and as of the National Credit Union Administration's data there are roughly 4,500 federally insured credit unions serving over 140 million members in the U.S. Many serve immigrant and Spanish-speaking communities directly and accept an ITIN to open membership. Use the framework below to match your situation to a lender type before you fill out a single application.</p>
  <table>
    <thead><tr><th>Lender type</th><th>Best when you have…</th><th>ITIN acceptance</th><th>Watch-outs</th></tr></thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td>Credit union</td><td>Steady income, want to build a relationship, can become a member</td><td>Often yes; varies by union</td><td>May require membership + a small deposit first</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Community bank / CDFI</td><td>Local ties, prefer in-person help, documentation in hand</td><td>Frequently yes</td><td>Smaller branch network; fewer products</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Online lender</td><td>Thin credit but strong income, want speed</td><td>Varies widely, verify first</td><td>Higher rates; confirm ITIN policy before applying</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Secured / co-signed loan</td><td>Little or no U.S. credit history</td><td>Most accept with collateral or co-signer</td><td>Collateral is at risk if you default</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <h2>A simple decision framework</h2>
  <p>Run these checks in order. Each one narrows the field and protects your wallet before you commit:</p>
  <ol class="lead-list">
    <li><strong>Confirm ITIN acceptance in writing.</strong> The Consumer Financial Protection Bureau notes that lenders may accept an ITIN in place of an SSN, but it is a per-lender policy, not a rule. Ask directly and get it confirmed before you apply, a denial can still leave a hard-inquiry footprint.</li>
    <li><strong>Match the loan to the need.</strong> Use a personal loan for a defined, one-time expense you can repay on a fixed schedule, debt consolidation, a medical bill, or a planned purchase. For ongoing or revolving needs, a card may fit better; see <a href="/itin-credit-cards">ITIN credit cards</a>.</li>
    <li><strong>Compare the APR, not the monthly payment.</strong> A lower monthly payment often hides a longer term and more total interest. The APR rolls rate plus fees into one number you can compare across lenders.</li>
    <li><strong>Secured first if your file is thin.</strong> If you have little U.S. credit history, a secured or co-signed loan is both easier to get and cheaper, and on-time payments build the history that unlocks unsecured loans later.</li>
    <li><strong>Read the fee schedule.</strong> Origination fees, prepayment penalties, and late fees vary by lender. Two loans at the same rate can cost very different amounts once fees are counted.</li>
  </ol>
  <p>Why this matters: the CFPB's consumer complaint data consistently shows that surprise fees and terms borrowers didn't understand are among the most common loan complaints. Slowing down to compare APR and fees across two or three ITIN-friendly lenders is the single highest-leverage step you can take.</p>

  <h2>How a personal loan builds your credit</h2>
  <p>An installment loan that reports to the nationwide bureaus does double duty: it covers the expense and it builds your file. Payment history is the largest input into most credit scores, so a year of on-time personal-loan payments can meaningfully strengthen a thin ITIN credit profile, provided the lender reports to the bureaus. Confirm that it does before you sign; not every small lender reports. For the full picture of how ITIN files are built and matched, see our <a href="/itin-loans">complete ITIN loans guide</a> and <a href="/itin-vs-ssn">ITIN vs SSN</a> explainer.</p>

  <h2>Tips to get approved</h2>
  <ul class="lead-list">
    <li>Document steady income with pay stubs, tax returns, or bank statements.</li>
    <li>Consider a credit union you can join, they're often the most ITIN-friendly.</li>
    <li>Offer collateral or add a co-signer if your credit history is limited.</li>
    <li>Compare several lenders; rates and approval criteria vary a lot.</li>
    <li>Keep your ITIN current, an expired ITIN can stall verification; the IRS publishes which ITINs need renewal.</li>
  </ul>
</MoneyPageLayout>
